<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1970" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Leucotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leucotrichia chiriquiensis" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiriquiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Leucotrichia chiriquiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. botosaneanui" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="botosaneanui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. botosaneanui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. hispida" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="hispida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. hispida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. viridis" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. viridis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on a similar appearance of the phallus, as discussed under 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. botosaneanui" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="botosaneanui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. botosaneanui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species can most swiftly be identified as distinct from the others based on the structural modifications of the antennae and head.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77371.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/713492" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
